The government has maintained that the IEBC must have powers to use a manual voting system because technology is susceptible to hacking, virus attacks and mechanical breakdown.This comes amid claims by the US government that Russia hacked its system and helped President-elect Donald Trump win the November 8 polls against Democratic candidate Hillary Clinton. The government said on Friday no one person is in full control of the process, hence nobody can explain any hitch soon after it occurs.It accused Cord of planning to rig the August 8 polls by hacking the system. The state said Cord legislators have also accused Jubilee of sinister plans. Government spokesperson Eric Kiraithe said al Shabab would like to destabilise the country by tampering with technological transmission of results to plunge the country into another wave of violence.